SECT. 5.—‘1'he crimes of Oppianicus.

We now return to Statius Albius Oppianicus (α), for the purpose of giving a history of his career as detailed by Cicero. A rapid summary, embracing most of the following particulars, will be found in Chapter 44.

1. He poisoned his wife Cluentia (η), sister of the elder Cluentius, and therefore paternal aunt (amita) of the defendant. This is the first in order of his enumerated crimes. (10.)

2. He poisoned Auria (ρ), wife of his brother C. Oppianicus (y), she being, at the time, pregnant. (11.)

3. He poisoned his brother C. Oppianicus (γ), and by the triple murder secured his inheritance. (11.)

4. On the death of his brother—in—law Numerius Magius (μ), he induced the widow to procure abortion in order that he might evade the will of Magius and secure the whole inherit-ance, of which he fraudulently gained possession. He then married the woman five months after her husband’s death, but the union lasted for but a brief period. (12.)

5. He poisoned, through the instrumentality of an itiner- ating quack (pharmacopola circumforaneus), his mother-in- law Dinaea (ι), the grandmother of young Oppianicus (β), who had made the boy her heir. After her death, he obtained possession of the will, made many erasures, and then, fearing detecti0n‚ transcribed it on new tablets and attached forged attestations. (7, 14.)
